HEADWORD: Tympany
<hw>Tym"pa*ny</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ a
kettledrum. See <er>Tympanites</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A flatulent distention of the belly;
tympanites.</def> <rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, inflation; conceit; bombast;
turgidness.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Thine's a <xex>tympany</xex> of sense.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A plethoric a tautologic <qex>tympany</qex> of sentence.</q>
<rj><qau>De Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tynd</ent>⟦br⟧
